  "prompt": "Why was the wax museum in Philadelphia built?",
  "response": "The wax museum in Philadelphia, known as the Philadelphia Wax Museum of Historical Figures, was built to serve several purposes. Primarily, it was created to educate the public about important historical figures and events through realistic and life-sized wax figures. The museum aimed to offer an engaging and interactive experience that could bring history to life, allowing visitors to connect with the past in a unique way.\n\nAdditionally, the museum was part of a broader trend during the 19th and 20th centuries, where wax museums became popular attractions in many cities, aimed at entertaining and informing visitors. The Philadelphia Wax Museum specifically focused on local history and notable figures from Pennsylvania and the United States, showcasing the city's rich cultural heritage. Overall, the museum sought to blend education with entertainment, making history accessible and interesting to a wide audience.",
